<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<h3>Is Jupiter a DEX or a DEX aggregator?</h3>

<p>Jupiter is primarily a <strong>DEX aggregator</strong> - it routes your swap across all major Solana DEXs (Raydium, Orca, Meteora, Phoenix, OpenBook) to find the best price. Most traders refer to it as a "DEX" because the user experience is identical to trading on a single DEX, but Jupiter itself does not host liquidity pools - it aggregates them.</p>



<h3>Can I trade meme coins on Coinbase in 2026?</h3>

<p>Yes - Coinbase lists approximately 30-40 Solana-based meme coins including $BONK, $WIF, $POPCAT, $MOG, and $DKING. However, it does not list the thousands of smaller, newer meme tokens that launch daily on Solana DEXs. For early-stage tokens, DEXs are the only option.</p>



<h3>Do DEXs report my trades to the IRS?</h3>

<p>As of May 2026, most DEX frontends do not automatically issue 1099-DA forms. However, the <strong>DeFi Broker Rule</strong> - which would require certain DEX operators to collect user data and report transactions - is under legal challenge. Regardless, <strong>you are legally required to self-report all DEX trades</strong> on your tax return. The blockchain record is permanent and traceable.</p>



<h3>Which is safer for large amounts - CEX or DEX?</h3>

<p>For amounts over $50,000, there is no simple answer. On a CEX, you trust the exchange's security but benefit from institutional insurance, proof-of-reserves, and customer support. On a DEX, you have full self-custody but bear all security risk yourself. The recommended approach: split your holdings. Keep trading capital on a hardware-wallet-connected DEX, and long-term holdings on a cold storage wallet, with only active trade funds on exchanges.</p>



<h3>What is the minimum amount to start trading meme coins on Solana?</h3>

<p>You can start trading with as little as <strong>$10</strong>. Solana's gas fees are fractions of a cent ($0.0002-$0.01 per transaction), so even micro-trades are economically viable. Buy $10 worth of SOL on Coinbase, withdraw to Phantom, and start swapping on Jupiter. For serious returns, most traders recommend starting with at least $200-$500.</p>



<h3>Are limit orders available on Solana DEXs?</h3>

<p>Yes - <strong>Jupiter Limit Order</strong> and <strong>Phoenix DEX</strong> both support limit orders on Solana. Jupiter's limit order feature routes through serum-style order books and fills at your specified price. However, liquidity on DEX limit orders is thinner than CEX order books, so large limit orders may not fill as quickly on DEXs.</p>



<h3>Can I use the same wallet for CEX and DEX trading?</h3>

<p>Yes, but it's not recommended for security reasons. Your DEX trading wallet should remain air-gapped from your CEX account to prevent any potential account-level correlation or freeze risks. Transfer SOL from CEX to your DEX wallet when you want to trade; transfer profits back to CEX when you want to cash out to fiat.</p>



<h3>Which exchange type has better customer support?</h3>

<p>CEXs win decisively on customer support. Coinbase and Kraken offer 24/7 phone, chat, and email support with dedicated teams for account recovery, frozen funds, and technical issues. DEX support is limited to community Discord channels, documentation, and community forums. If you lose funds on a DEX through user error, there is no one to call.</p>



<h3>What happens if the Solana network goes down while I have an open position?</h3>

<p>Solana has experienced network outages in the past (most notably in 2022 with multiple multi-hour halts). In 2024-2026, Solana's reliability has improved dramatically with the implementation of QUIC, local fee markets, and stake-weighted QoS - no major outages in over 18 months. However, if the network were to halt, DEX positions would be stuck until the chain resumes. CEX positions would remain tradeable within the exchange's internal order book, even if the Solana network is paused, though deposits/withdrawals would be delayed.</p>



